╔═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║  SHIP'S ARCHIVE: cat                                          ║
║  Classification: Core Tool                                    ║
╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

┌─ ORIGIN STORY ─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  Created by Ken Thompson in 1969 for the first Unix system.   │
│  The name is short for "concatenate" - to link things         │
│  together in a chain. Thompson needed a way to join multiple  │
│  files and display their combined contents. The command has   │
│  remained essentially unchanged for over 50 years.            │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ MENTAL MODEL ─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  Think of cat as a FUNNEL that pours file contents to your    │
│  screen (stdout):                                              │
│                                                                │
│     file1.txt ──┐                                              │
│                 ├──▶ [cat] ──▶ stdout (your screen)           │
│     file2.txt ──┘                                              │
│                                                                │
│  When given multiple files, it chains them together:          │
│                                                                │
│     cat part1.txt part2.txt part3.txt                         │
│         ↓           ↓           ↓                              │
│     [contents1][contents2][contents3] → screen                │
│                                                                │
│  Despite its design for concatenation, most people use it     │
│  simply to view single files quickly.                         │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ CONNECTIONS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  • Works well with: pipes (cat file | grep), less, head, tail │
│  • Alternatives: less (for long files), head/tail (for parts) │
│  • Builds toward: Understanding stdin/stdout, pipelines       │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ ARIA'S INSIGHT ───────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  "A common mistake is using 'cat file | grep pattern' when    │
│  'grep pattern file' works directly. This is called 'useless  │
│  use of cat' - but don't feel bad, even experienced engineers │
│  do it. The habit of reading files through cat is deeply      │
│  ingrained. Use what feels natural while learning."           │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
